{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627777","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627777"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:52:04+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:52:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17151"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17151"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0,0.91,0,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9841"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76987"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9841","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9841"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62493"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9869"},{"type":"tags","id":"9885"},{"type":"tags","id":"9886"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23044"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23048"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76987","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/76987"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe lymphatic system plays a crucial role in fluid homeostasis by returning excess tissue fluid to the circulation. This process begins with the formation of lymph in the interstitial space.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of lymph formation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Active secretion by lymphatic endothelial cells","Direct conversion of plasma proteins","Net filtration of fluid from capillaries into interstitial space","Cellular production of lymphatic fluid","Osmotic movement of water against pressure gradient"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENet filtration of fluid from capillaries into interstitial space\u003C/strong\u003E occurs due to the balance between hydrostatic and oncotic pressures at the capillary bed. When capillary hydrostatic pressure exceeds the combined forces of plasma oncotic pressure and tissue pressure, fluid moves into the interstitial space forming lymph.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive secretion by lymphatic endothelial cells\u003C/strong\u003E - Lymphatic endothelial cells do not secrete lymph; they form vessels that transport it\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect conversion of plasma proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - Plasma proteins do not undergo conversion to form lymph; they move with fluid filtration\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECellular production of lymphatic fluid\u003C/strong\u003E - Cells do not produce lymph; it forms from existing interstitial fluid\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsmotic movement of water against pressure gradient\u003C/strong\u003E - Lymph formation follows, not opposes, pressure gradients\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe lymphatic system then collects this excess interstitial fluid and returns it to the circulation via lymphatic vessels that contain one-way valves and undergo rhythmic contractions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Lymph formation occurs when hydrostatic pressure exceeds oncotic pressure in capillary beds, causing fluid filtration into interstitial space.","The primary forces driving lymph formation are hydrostatic pressure, oncotic pressure, and tissue pressure following Starling\u0027s principles.","Lymphatic vessels actively pump and transport excess interstitial fluid back to the circulation."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62493"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17151"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62493"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T21:57:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T21:58:31+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9841"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"76987"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"http